<tt>Sat Jun 28  2:28:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tom,<br><br>
Since you didn't answer my questions, I feel no need to explicitly answer yours.  I will point out that there were &quot;invasions&quot; of the South by the North, not in the Vietnamese &quot;Civil War,&quot; but in ours.  <br><br>
I also agree that we were viewed by some Vietnamese as &quot;invaders,&quot; but not by all.  The Vietnamese people I met and talked to didn't think that way, either in Vietnam or at Oregon State University.  We were formally invited into this thing, whether you recognize the Diem government's right to do so or not.  <br><br>
Oh yes, we did sign the Geneva Accords, and tried to abide by them.  This is why the NVA could use Laos and Cambodia as a sanctuary for most of the war.<br><br>
Nurse Ratchet,<br><br>
World War II guns--give me a break.  AK47s hadn't been invented for that war, and neither had SKS sniper rifles.  What we are talking about is a highly-trained, well equipped army with good weapons when we speak of the NVA.  <br><br>
The difference between My Lai and what the VC were doing is a difference in scope, intent, command and control, and results.  If the things that the VC were doing made it into Life Magazine, and onto the TV during that time, perhaps perceptions of what was happening, and who was doing what to whom, would have changed.  That might also have changed the outcome, because &quot;perceptions are reality&quot; regardless of the facts.<br><br>

